to continually poke fun at presitator Xi Jinping
for centuries.

77
00:03:33,410 --> 00:03:37,060
“He still wants that sweet, sweet honey.

78
00:03:37,060 --> 00:03:38,190
Haha.

79
00:03:38,190 --> 00:03:39,319
Haha.

80
00:03:39,319 --> 00:03:42,329
Anyway, there are more ways these economic
weapons

81
00:03:42,329 --> 00:03:44,810
could backfire for China.

82
00:03:44,810 --> 00:03:47,019
For example, the Communist Party’s tactic

83
00:03:47,019 --> 00:03:50,060
of going after American farmers to hurt Trump....

84
00:03:50,060 --> 00:03:51,590
is not working very well.

85
00:03:51,590 --> 00:03:54,599
It’s true, a lot of American farmers are
hurting,

86
00:03:54,599 --> 00:03:56,879
as China has stopped buying their products.

87
00:03:56,879 --> 00:03:59,500
And I get it, the Communist Party naturally
assume

88
00:03:59,500 --> 00:04:02,560
the peasants will rise up against their oppressor.

89
00:04:02,560 --> 00:04:05,019
The problem is, a lot of American farmers

90
00:04:05,019 --> 00:04:06,950
don’t see Trump as the oppressor.

91
00:04:06,950 --> 00:04:08,819
They’re sticking with him.

92
00:04:08,819 --> 00:04:11,290
A lot of them see Trump as helping farmers

93
00:04:11,290 --> 00:04:13,319
stand up to the real oppressor:

94
00:04:13,319 --> 00:04:15,040
The Chinese Communist Party—

95
00:04:15,040 --> 00:04:16,040
which is, after all,

96
00:04:16,040 --> 00:04:18,950
the one actually *trying* to hurt American
farmers.

97
00:04:18,950 --> 00:04:22,190
This CNBC article cites a farmer from Illinois
as saying,

98
00:04:22,190 --> 00:04:25,710
“most farmers are more concerned about getting
the situation solved

99
00:04:25,710 --> 00:04:27,120
than pointing fingers.

100
00:04:27,120 --> 00:04:29,880
But if they were to place blame,

101
00:04:29,880 --> 00:04:31,900
most of it would be on China,

102
00:04:31,900 --> 00:04:34,500
and the rest would be on previous presidents

103
00:04:34,500 --> 00:04:36,970
who could have solved the trade imbalances
more easily

104
00:04:36,970 --> 00:04:38,820
15 or 20 years ago.”

105
00:04:38,820 --> 00:04:41,600
And it also helps that Trump is using some
of the money

106
00:04:41,600 --> 00:04:45,650
the US is getting from Chinese tariffs to
subsidize US farmers.

107
00:04:45,650 --> 00:04:48,470
And as for the Chinese central bank allowing
the Chinese yuan

108
00:04:48,470 --> 00:04:50,480
to get weaker against the dollar...yes,

109
00:04:50,480 --> 00:04:52,650
it helps Chinese exports,

110
00:04:52,650 --> 00:04:55,460
but it also hurts Chinese companies—

111
00:04:55,460 --> 00:04:58,420
companies that have borrowed US money.

112
00:04:58,420 --> 00:05:01,500
See, “Dollar-denominated debt held by Chinese
firms

113
00:05:01,500 --> 00:05:05,070
is now more than 1.5 trillion dollars.”

114
00:05:05,070 --> 00:05:07,110
That means that Chinese companies have *borrowed*

115
00:05:07,110 --> 00:05:10,110
more than 1.5 trillion US dollars...

116
00:05:10,110 --> 00:05:13,640
that have to be paid back in US dollars.

117
00:05:13,640 --> 00:05:14,640
Why?

118
00:05:14,640 --> 00:05:16,050
Because the US Federal Reserve

119
00:05:16,050 --> 00:05:18,870
has kept interest rates at historic lows

120
00:05:18,870 --> 00:05:21,820
since the 2008 financial crisis.

121
00:05:21,820 --> 00:05:23,670
And Chinese companies that needed to borrow
money

122
00:05:23,670 --> 00:05:27,540
to make big investments—like real estate
developers—

123
00:05:27,540 --> 00:05:30,530
realized it would be cheaper to borrow *US
dollars*

124
00:05:30,530 --> 00:05:34,840
than to borrow Chinese yuan to pay for all
that construction...

125
00:05:34,840 --> 00:05:38,030
and those fancy real estate displays.

126
00:05:38,030 --> 00:05:39,030
At the same time,

127
00:05:39,030 --> 00:05:40,620
the Chinese financial sector

128
00:05:40,620 --> 00:05:43,520
also took advantage of low US interest rates,

129
00:05:43,520 --> 00:05:46,840
and borrowed cheap US dollars to invest in
other things,

130
00:05:46,840 --> 00:05:49,810
hoping to get a bigger return on investment.

131
00:05:49,810 --> 00:05:52,190
As you can see in this chart from Axios,

132
00:05:52,190 --> 00:05:55,500
Chinese borrowing has skyrocketed over the
past decade.

133
00:05:55,500 --> 00:05:57,520
But now that China’s currency is weaker,

134
00:05:57,520 --> 00:06:00,320
it’s more expensive to pay back all that
debt.

135
00:06:00,320 --> 00:06:03,710
Let’s say, for example, you’re a Chinese
real estate developer

136
00:06:03,710 --> 00:06:06,240
and you borrowed money for construction.

137
00:06:06,240 --> 00:06:09,820
You paid in yuan to borrow a billion US dollars.

138
00:06:09,820 --> 00:06:12,840
But because the yuan is roughly 2% weaker
now,

139
00:06:12,840 --> 00:06:16,140
it’s 2% more expensive to pay it back.

140
00:06:16,140 --> 00:06:20,980
And that extra amount you owe is the equivalent
of $20 million dollars.

141
00:06:20,980 --> 00:06:22,640
So for the Chinese economy overall

142
00:06:22,640 --> 00:06:25,310
that borrowed 1.5 trillion dollars—

143
00:06:25,310 --> 00:06:27,970
they now owe a collective 30 billion dollars

144
00:06:27,970 --> 00:06:31,140
more than they did just two weeks ago.

145
00:06:31,140 --> 00:06:34,520
30 billion dollars is a is a lot of money.

146
00:06:34,520 --> 00:06:37,220
It makes my student loan lender seem like
an angel.

147
00:06:37,220 --> 00:06:41,220
An angel that’ll break my kneecaps if I
don’t repay, but still.

148
00:06:41,220 --> 00:06:42,960
And if the yuan keeps falling,

149
00:06:42,960 --> 00:06:45,360
the higher cost of repaying US dollars

150
00:06:45,360 --> 00:06:48,430
could get really bad for Chinese companies.

151
00:06:48,430 --> 00:06:50,260
Now as I said, a weaker yuan

152
00:06:50,260 --> 00:06:53,310
does help boost Chinese exports to the US—

153
00:06:53,310 --> 00:06:55,620
but that’s a long-term prospect,

154
00:06:55,620 --> 00:06:58,790
and exports probably won’t go up enough
to compensate.

155
00:06:58,790 --> 00:07:02,480
Especially because no one wants to buy their
stupid love pandas!

156
00:07:02,480 --> 00:07:04,480
So why does all this matter?

157
00:07:04,480 --> 00:07:06,010
Because this debt problem could have

158
00:07:06,010 --> 00:07:08,520
a domino effect on the Chinese economy—

159
00:07:08,520 --> 00:07:11,470
like layoffs that lead to mass unemployment,

160
00:07:11,470 --> 00:07:15,100
or a nationwide economic downturn if credit
dries up.

161
00:07:15,100 --> 00:07:16,100
Which is to say,

162
00:07:16,100 --> 00:07:17,620
the Chinese Communist Party’s methods

163
00:07:17,620 --> 00:07:20,100
at fighting back against the US tariffs

164
00:07:20,100 --> 00:07:24,860
could end up more like this.

